{"title_page": "Phil Spencer (business executive)", "text_new": "{{BLP primary sources|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Phil Spencer\n| image       = Phil Spencer Xbox.jpg\n| caption     = Spencer in 2015\n| birth_place = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1968|1|12}}{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n| nationality = American\n| other_names = P3 (gamertag)<ref>{{cite web |title=Phil Spencer (@XboxP3) {{!}} Twitter |url=https://twitter.com/XboxP3 |website=twitter.com |accessdate=26 June 2018 |language=en |quote=Gamer Tag: P3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ekberg |first1=Brian |title=Introducing Forza Motorsport 7's December Bounty Hunter: Phil Spencer - Xbox Wire |url=https://news.xbox.com/en-us/2017/12/11/introducing-forza-motorsport-7s-december-bounty-hunter-phil-spencer/ |website=news.xbox.com |accessdate=26 June 2018 |language=en-us |date=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n| alma mater = [[University of Washington]]\n| title      = Executive Vice President of Gaming at Microsoft\n| occupation  = Head executive of Microsoft's [[Xbox]] division\n}}\n\n'''Phil Spencer''' (born January 12, 1968) is an American business executive, who is the current executive vice-president of Gaming at [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Soper |first1=Taylor |title=Microsoft to accelerate growth in gaming as Xbox leader Phil Spencer joins senior leadership team |url=https://www.geekwire.com/2017/microsoft-accelerate-growth-gaming-xbox-leader-phil-spencer-joins-senior-leadership-team/ |website=GeekWire |publisher=GeekWire, LLC |date=19 September 2017}}</ref> He is currently the head of the [[Xbox]] brand and leads the global creative and engineering teams responsible for gaming at Microsoft.\n\n== Personal life ==\nSpencer earned a bachelor's [[Academic degree|degree]] from the [[University of Washington]] and currently serves on the boards of the First Tee of Greater Seattle and the Entertainment Software Association.<ref name=\"xboxbio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.xbox.com/es-CL/Press/Corporate/phil-spencer |title=Phil Spencer |publisher=Xbox.com |accessdate=2014-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160621123851/http://www.xbox.com/es-CL/Press/Corporate/phil-spencer |archivedate=2016-06-21 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nSpencer joined Microsoft in 1988 as an intern and has worked in a number of technical roles, leading the development of Microsoft's first CD-ROM-based titles (such as [[Encarta]]), development manager for [[Microsoft Money]], and general manager of Microsoft's online and offline consumer productivity products including Microsoft Works and Microsoft Picture It! <ref name=\"xboxbio\" /><ref name=\"ms\">{{cite web |url=http://www.microsoft.com/bizspark/kinectaccelerator/mentors/philspencer.aspx |publisher=Microsoft |title=Kinect Accelerator Mentor: Phil Spencer |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref>\n\nSpencer served as general manager of Microsoft Game Studios EMEA, working with Microsoft's European developers and studios such as Lionhead Studios and [[Rare (company)|Rare]] until 2008, when he became the general manager of Microsoft Studios, eventually becoming the studio's corporate vice president a year later.<ref name=\"ms\" /><ref name=\"time\">{{cite web |url=http://time.com/43939/welcome-phil-spencer-microsofts-new-xbox-everything-honcho/ |title=Welcome Phil Spencer, Microsoft's New Xbox-Everything Honcho |publisher=Time |date=2014-03-31 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref> He has participated in Microsoft's [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3]] conferences since 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/video-games/7890823/E3-2010-Phil-Spencer-interview.html |title=E3 2010: Phil Spencer interview |publisher=The Telegraph |date=2010-07-15 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.g4tv.com/videos/53413/phil-spencer-e3-2011-interview/ |title=Phil Spencer E3 2011 Interview |publisher=G4tv |date=2011-06-07 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/13yxve/microsoft-e3-2012--phil-spencer-post-conference-interview |title=E3 2012: Phil Spencer Post-Conference Interview |date=2012-06-05 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/86lf4h/xbox-one-e3-2013--phil-spencer-talks-xbox-one-lineup |title=E3 2013: Phil Spencer Talks Xbox One Lineup |publisher=GameTrailers |date=2013-06-10 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref>\n\nIn late March 2014, [[Satya Nadella]] announced in a corporate e-mail that Spencer was to \"lead the [[Xbox]], [[Xbox Live]], [[Groove Music]] and [[Microsoft Movies & TV|Movies & TV]] teams, and [[Microsoft Studios]]\" as part of the Windows and Devices division.<ref name=\"time\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/misc/2014/mar14/03-31corpemail.aspx |title=Satya Nadella email to employees on tuning our organization |publisher=Microsoft |date=2014-03-31 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Spencer was promoted to the Senior Leadership Team, gaining the title of Executive Vice President of Gaming and reporting directly to CEO [[Satya Nadella]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weinberger|first1=Matt|title=Microsoft Xbox boss Phil Spencer just got a big promotion, and will now report directly to CEO Satya Nadella|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/microsoft-xbox-phil-spencer-gets-promoted-to-executive-vice-president-2017-9|website=businessinsider.com|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Spencer delivered the keynote address at the 2018 [[DICE Summit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/02/23/the-deanbeat-microsofts-phil-spencer-steps-up-as-a-diversity-leader/|title=The DeanBeat: Microsoft's Phil Spencer steps up as a diversity leader|last=Takahashi|first=Dean|date=February 23, 2018|work=VentureBeat|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref> and spoke at the 2018 [[the Game Awards|Game Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/12/06/sony-microsoft-and-nintendo-get-up-on-stage-at-the-game-awards/|title=Sony, Microsoft, and Nintendo get up on stage at The Game Awards|date=December 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince taking over both Xbox and the Gaming division, Spencer has advocated for [[cross-platform play]], as well as launched key initiatives, such as reintroducing [[backward compatibility]] to the Xbox platform, the purchase of [[Mojang]], the further development and support of [[Minecraft]], the introduction of [[Xbox Game Pass]], launching the [[Xbox Adaptive Controller]], an increased focus on PC gaming, support of the [[Nintendo Switch]], the launch of [[xCloud]], and increasing the number of first-party development studios.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/phil-spencer-is-exactly-who-you-think-he-is/1100-6468846/ | title = Phil Spencer Is Exactly Who You Think He Is | first = Laura | last = Parker | date = December 19, 2019 | accessdate = January 19, 2020 | work =[[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Spencer spoke about the Xbox Series X confirming that it won't support VR. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/xbox-series-x-vr-would-be-pointless-right-now-claims-phil-spencer|title=Xbox Series X VR would be pointless right now, claims Phil Spencer|last=February 2020|first=Vic Hood 11|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://account.xbox.com/Profile?gamerTag=P3 Phil Spencer] [[Xbox Live]] profile\n\n{{Xbox Game Studios}}{{Microsoft}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spencer, Phil}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Microsoft employees]]\n[[Category:Video game businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:University of Washington alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Xbox]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP primary sources|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Phil Spencer\n| image       = Phil Spencer Xbox.jpg\n| caption     = Spencer in 2015\n| birth_place = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1968|1|12}}{{cn|date=May 2019}}\n| nationality = American\n| other_names = P3 (gamertag)<ref>{{cite web |title=Phil Spencer (@XboxP3) {{!}} Twitter |url=https://twitter.com/XboxP3 |website=twitter.com |accessdate=26 June 2018 |language=en |quote=Gamer Tag: P3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Ekberg |first1=Brian |title=Introducing Forza Motorsport 7's December Bounty Hunter: Phil Spencer - Xbox Wire |url=https://news.xbox.com/en-us/2017/12/11/introducing-forza-motorsport-7s-december-bounty-hunter-phil-spencer/ |website=news.xbox.com |accessdate=26 June 2018 |language=en-us |date=11 December 2017}}</ref>\n| alma mater = [[University of Washington]]\n| title      = Executive Vice President of Gaming at Microsoft\n| occupation  = Head executive of Microsoft's [[Xbox]] division\n}}\n\n'''Phil Spencer''' (born January 12, 1968) is an American business executive, who is the current executive vice-president of Gaming at [[Microsoft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Soper |first1=Taylor |title=Microsoft to accelerate growth in gaming as Xbox leader Phil Spencer joins senior leadership team |url=https://www.geekwire.com/2017/microsoft-accelerate-growth-gaming-xbox-leader-phil-spencer-joins-senior-leadership-team/ |website=GeekWire |publisher=GeekWire, LLC |date=19 September 2017}}</ref> He is currently the head of the [[Xbox]] brand and leads the global creative and engineering teams responsible for gaming at Microsoft.\n\n== Personal life ==\nSpencer earned a bachelor's [[Academic degree|degree]] from the [[University of Washington]] and currently serves on the boards of the First Tee of Greater Seattle and the Entertainment Software Association.<ref name=\"xboxbio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.xbox.com/es-CL/Press/Corporate/phil-spencer |title=Phil Spencer |publisher=Xbox.com |accessdate=2014-04-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160621123851/http://www.xbox.com/es-CL/Press/Corporate/phil-spencer |archivedate=2016-06-21 }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nSpencer joined Microsoft in 1988 as an intern and has worked in a number of technical roles, leading the development of Microsoft's first CD-ROM-based titles (such as [[Encarta]]), development manager for [[Microsoft Money]], and general manager of Microsoft's online and offline consumer productivity products including Microsoft Works and Microsoft Picture It! <ref name=\"xboxbio\" /><ref name=\"ms\">{{cite web |url=http://www.microsoft.com/bizspark/kinectaccelerator/mentors/philspencer.aspx |publisher=Microsoft |title=Kinect Accelerator Mentor: Phil Spencer |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref>\n\nSpencer served as general manager of Microsoft Game Studios EMEA, working with Microsoft's European developers and studios such as Lionhead Studios and [[Rare (company)|Rare]] until 2008, when he became the general manager of Microsoft Studios, eventually becoming the studio's corporate vice president a year later.<ref name=\"ms\" /><ref name=\"time\">{{cite web |url=http://time.com/43939/welcome-phil-spencer-microsofts-new-xbox-everything-honcho/ |title=Welcome Phil Spencer, Microsoft's New Xbox-Everything Honcho |publisher=Time |date=2014-03-31 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref> He has participated in Microsoft's [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3]] conferences since 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/video-games/7890823/E3-2010-Phil-Spencer-interview.html |title=E3 2010: Phil Spencer interview |publisher=The Telegraph |date=2010-07-15 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.g4tv.com/videos/53413/phil-spencer-e3-2011-interview/ |title=Phil Spencer E3 2011 Interview |publisher=G4tv |date=2011-06-07 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/13yxve/microsoft-e3-2012--phil-spencer-post-conference-interview |title=E3 2012: Phil Spencer Post-Conference Interview |date=2012-06-05 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/86lf4h/xbox-one-e3-2013--phil-spencer-talks-xbox-one-lineup |title=E3 2013: Phil Spencer Talks Xbox One Lineup |publisher=GameTrailers |date=2013-06-10 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref>\n\nIn late March 2014, [[Satya Nadella]] announced in a corporate e-mail that Spencer was to \"lead the [[Xbox]], [[Xbox Live]], [[Groove Music]] and [[Microsoft Movies & TV|Movies & TV]] teams, and [[Microsoft Studios]]\".<ref name=\"time\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/news/misc/2014/mar14/03-31corpemail.aspx |title=Satya Nadella email to employees on tuning our organization |publisher=Microsoft |date=2014-03-31 |accessdate=2014-04-06}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, Spencer was promoted to the Senior Leadership Team, gaining the title of Executive Vice President of Gaming within the company. He reports directly to CEO [[Satya Nadella]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weinberger|first1=Matt|title=Microsoft Xbox boss Phil Spencer just got a big promotion, and will now report directly to CEO Satya Nadella|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/microsoft-xbox-phil-spencer-gets-promoted-to-executive-vice-president-2017-9|website=businessinsider.com|accessdate=19 September 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Spencer delivered the keynote address at the 2018 [[DICE Summit]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/02/23/the-deanbeat-microsofts-phil-spencer-steps-up-as-a-diversity-leader/|title=The DeanBeat: Microsoft's Phil Spencer steps up as a diversity leader|last=Takahashi|first=Dean|date=February 23, 2018|work=VentureBeat|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nSpencer spoke at the 2018 [[the Game Awards|Game Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/12/06/sony-microsoft-and-nintendo-get-up-on-stage-at-the-game-awards/|title=Sony, Microsoft, and Nintendo get up on stage at The Game Awards|date=December 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSince taking over both Xbox and the Gaming division, Spencer has advocated for [[cross-platform play]], as well as launched key initiatives, such as reintroducing [[backward compatibility]] to the Xbox platform, the purchase of [[Mojang]], the further development and support of [[Minecraft]], the introduction of [[Xbox Game Pass]], launching the [[Xbox Adaptive Controller]], an increased focus on PC gaming, support of the [[Nintendo Switch]], the launch of [[xCloud]], and increasing the number of first-party development studios.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamespot.com/articles/phil-spencer-is-exactly-who-you-think-he-is/1100-6468846/ | title = Phil Spencer Is Exactly Who You Think He Is | first = Laura | last = Parker | date = December 19, 2019 | accessdate = January 19, 2020 | work =[[GameSpot]] }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, Spencer spoke about the Xbox Series X confirming that it won't support VR. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/xbox-series-x-vr-would-be-pointless-right-now-claims-phil-spencer|title=Xbox Series X VR would be pointless right now, claims Phil Spencer|last=February 2020|first=Vic Hood 11|website=TechRadar|language=en|access-date=2020-02-20}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Twitter}}\n* [https://account.xbox.com/Profile?gamerTag=P3 Phil Spencer] [[Xbox Live]] profile\n\n{{Xbox Game Studios}}{{Microsoft}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Spencer, Phil}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Microsoft employees]]\n[[Category:Video game businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in software]]\n[[Category:American computer businesspeople]]\n[[Category:University of Washington alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Xbox]]\n", "name_user": "MSPRUPDATE", "label": "safe", "comment": "Clarified organizational structure in 2014, minor clarity edits.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil_Spencer_(business_executive)"}
